\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Cross-bridge models have for many years become more complex by increasing the number of biochemical states, without becoming more realistic by incorporating new structural and mechanical data at the molecular level. Williams et al. describe a new cross-bridge model that is a major step in the right direction. Their primary, long-term motivation is to investigate the Frank-Starling mechanism of the heart by predicting the influence of filament lattice spacing on cardiac muscle mechanics. A new cross-bridge model is a prerequisite for such an investigation because existing cross-bridge models do not incorporate the distance between thick and thin filaments as a variable. Not only do the authors introduce a new and more realistic model, the also identify a simpler and computationally more tractable version that captures the key features of the more complex model, but will speed up their future simulations. }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Major concerns }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch The manuscript is missing any discussion of how the model kinetics have been adapted for cardiac myosin, and what cardiac myosin (human or small rodent, alpha- or beta-MHC isoform) is the target. }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch TODO: Get refs organized by source isoform}{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch What parameters in the model would be altered to allow simulations of these various myosins, primarily compliance or kinetics, or is it necessary for both to co-vary? }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch It would seem appropriate to briefly consider in discussion the possibility that disease-related mutations in cardiac myosin might have their major effects through changes in cross-bridge compliance. For example, see two papers from Kraft and colleagues (K\'f6hler, J., G. Winkler, I. Schulte, T. Scholz, W. McKenna, B. Brenner, and T. Kraft. 2002. Mutation of the myosin converter domain alters cross-bridge elasticity. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 99:3557-3562; Seebohm, B., F. Matinmehr, J. K\'f6hler, A. Francino, F. Navarro-Lopez, A. Perrot, C. Ozcelik, W. J. McKenna, B. Brenner, and T. Kraft. 2009. Cardiomyopathy}{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch mutations reveal variable region of myosin converter as major element of cross-bridge compliance. Biophys. J. 97:806-824). Thin filament mutant's effects on compliance might also be important in the broader model, but that is beyond the scope of the current manuscript. The model may ultimately provide important insight into cardiac disease mechanisms. }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch What are the implications for shortening velocity when the new models are missing the asymmetric cross-bridge detachment rate that were built into the 1sXB model? Williams' approach that avoids discontinuous functions is certainly more appealing, but is it as successful as Huxley's at explaining such a wide variety of physiological phenomena? }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Williams introduces arbitrary "efficiency factors" for the free energy of the attached states (page 10). What is the sensitivity of the model to the values used? }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch The efficiency factors used on page 10 are the values used in Tanner et al. (2007) and are derived from the work of Pate and Cooke (1989). They are governed by the drop in free energy from the unbound state to the loosely bound state and from the loosely bound state to the strongly bound state.  This was cited and discussed in an unclear fashion that we've attempted to improve. }{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
