\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Minor Comments }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch 1. It would be helpful if throughout the text the terms used to describe spatial components of force and movement were standardized. In my view the term 'direction of contraction' is ambiguous and should be replaced by something like 'parallel to the long axis of the myofilaments', which could be shortened subsequently to 'fiber axis' or similar. This would be less distracting, as the terms 'contraction' or 'shortening' are loaded with too many other connotations. }{\f0\fs22\b\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch "The long axis of the myofilaments" is far more clear and has been incorporated.}{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch TODO: Should that be "axes" of the myofilaments? There are more than one myofilament after all, but they do share an axis, kind of. }{\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
